    "<a href=\"https://colab.research.google.com/github/EvenSol/NeqSim-Colab/blob/master/notebooks/thermodynamics/ThermodynamicandphysicalpropertiesofCO2.ipynb\" target=\"_parent\"><img src=\"https://colab.research.google.com/assets/colab-badge.svg\" alt=\"Open In Colab\"/></a>\n",
    "\n",
    "# Thermodynamic and physical properties of CO₂ with NeqSim\n",
    "\n",
    "This tutorial is for process, pipeline, flow-assurance, CCS, and energy engineers who\n",
    "need reproducible carbon-dioxide property calculations and a clear path from an\n",
    "equation of state to a process model.\n",
    "\n",
    "**Prerequisites:** Python basics and introductory thermodynamics. Pressure is absolute\n",
    "(`bara`) throughout. Temperatures are reported in degrees Celsius and converted to\n",
    "kelvin inside thermodynamic models where needed.\n",
    "\n",
    "## Learning objectives\n",
    "\n",
    "By the end, you will be able to:\n",
    "\n",
    "1. calculate CO₂ density, compressibility, heat capacity, speed of sound, and viscosity;\n",
    "2. compare SRK, Peng–Robinson, Span–Wagner, and EOS-CG model predictions;\n",
    "3. reproduce a low-pressure EOS-CG benchmark and an ideal-gas limiting check;\n",
    "4. calculate and interpret the phase envelope of a CO₂-rich stream with trace gases;\n",
    "5. evaluate energy-conserving depressurization while respecting the CO₂ triple point;\n",
    "6. use solid-phase calculations as a qualitative dry-ice risk screen;\n",
    "7. compose `Stream`, `Cooler`, `ThrottlingValve`, `Separator`, and `ProcessSystem`;\n",
    "8. audit mass, component, cooler-energy, and valve-enthalpy balances; and\n",
    "9. rerun the workflow for independent cooling scenarios."
   ]
  },
